attributes.text:
Remote data business object with intelligent cache managment.

  • Supports localStorage for storing data between application runs.
  • Supports HTTP-proxying for cross-domain communication
  • Supports basic HTTP authentification
  • Make use of modification dates to optimize data loading via GET

Fired whenever a communication with a service has been completed.

Identify whether the event is interesting for you by the events ID property.
Adds basic authentification data to the request given on the properties {@link #user} and {@link #password}.
Identifier of the service to communicate to
Optional map of parameters to patch URL with / use for filter method
Any supported HTTP method: OPTIONS, GET, POST, PUT, DELETE and HEAD
Data to attach to a POST request
Main communication routine. Called by most developer-level APIs.
Returns a unique ID based on the service/param combination
Returns the cache ID for the given argument set.
Patches the given URL to fill template fields with given params and add support for proxying of the request.
Clears the cache for the given service & param combination. Also deletes data stored on local storage.

Returns the (computed) value of the property authMethod.

For further details take a look at the property definition: {@link #authMethod}.

Reads an entry (all data stored for the given service/param combination) from the cache.

Each entry consists of the keys data and type (the data and type of data) and the timestamps created, checked and modified. There is also an id which could be used in an easy way to compare whether one have used the same version of cache entry before. This ID is updated every time new data was loaded.
Returns the entry as stored in the cache.
Returns the value of the given field inside the cache for the given service.
Value stored on the given field or null

Returns the cache status for the given service.

  • 0: cache is disabled
  • 1: nothing cached
  • 2: cache is old
  • 3: cache is valid
